---
const stateData = {
  AL: { name: "Alabama", rate: "2.7%", avgCost: 385 },
  AK: { name: "Alaska", rate: "2.5%", avgCost: 395 },
  // ... other states
};

const maxRate = Math.max(...Object.values(stateData).map(state => parseFloat(state.rate)));
const minRate = Math.min(...Object.values(stateData).map(state => parseFloat(state.rate)));
const avgRate = (Object.values(stateData).reduce((sum, state) => sum + parseFloat(state.rate), 0) / Object.keys(stateData).length).toFixed(1);
---

<section class="key-info">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Understanding Unemployment Costs</h2>
    
    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="card">
        <h3>What are Unemployment Costs?</h3>
        
        <div class="cost-sections">
          <div class="cost-section">
            <h4>Federal Unemployment Tax (FUTA)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>6% base rate on first $7,000 of employee wages</li>
              <li>Maximum of $420 per employee annually</li>
              <li>Most employers qualify for a 5.4% credit, reducing effective rate to 0.6%</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="cost-section">
            <h4>State Unemployment Tax (SUTA)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Tax rates typically range between 1% and 8% of taxable wages</li>
              <li>Each state sets its own taxable wage base</li>
              <li>New employers receive a standard rate before establishing an experience rating</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="cost-section">
            <h4>Real Cost Impact</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Average claim payout of $4,200, potentially reaching up to $12,000</li>
              <li>Tax rate increases can affect employer costs for three years</li>
              <li>A single claim can increase state tax premiums by $4,000 to $7,000 over three years</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="cost-section">
            <h4>Cost Factors</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Industry type (higher turnover industries face higher rates)</li>
              <li>Company's history of unemployment claims</li>
              <li>State-specific regulations and wage bases</li>
              <li>Timely payment of state unemployment taxes</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cost-summary">
          <div class="summary-box">
            <strong>0.75%</strong>
            <span>Average UI tax rate of total payroll</span>
          </div>
          <div class="summary-box">
            <strong>$350</strong>
            <span>Average cost per employee</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card">
        <h3>State Tax Rate Summary</h3>
        <div class="rate-summary">
          <div class="summary-stat">
            <span class="label">Lowest Rate</span>
            <span class="value">{minRate}%</span>
            <span class="state">{
              Object.entries(stateData).find(([_, state]) => parseFloat(state.rate) === minRate)?.[1].name
            }</span>
          </div>
          <div class="summary-stat">
            <span class="label">Average Rate</span>
            <span class="value">{avgRate}%</span>
            <span class="state">National Average</span>
          </div>
          <div class="summary-stat">
            <span class="label">Highest Rate</span>
            <span class="value">{maxRate}%</span>
            <span class="state">{
              Object.entries(stateData).find(([_, state]) => parseFloat(state.rate) === maxRate)?.[1].name
            }</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tax-insights">
          <h4>Key Tax Rate Insights</h4>
          <div class="insights-grid">
            <div class="insight-item">
              <span class="insight-label">Highest Wage Base</span>
              <span class="insight-value">$72,800</span>
              <span class="insight-detail">Washington State</span>
            </div>
            <div class="insight-item">
              <span class="insight-label">Lowest Wage Base</span>
              <span class="insight-value">$7,000</span>
              <span class="insight-detail">Multiple States</span>
            </div>
            <div class="insight-item">
              <span class="insight-label">Highest New Employer Rate</span>
              <span class="insight-value">4.1%</span>
              <span class="insight-detail">New York</span>
            </div>
            <div class="insight-item">
              <span class="insight-label">Lowest New Employer Rate</span>
              <span class="insight-value">0.5%</span>
              <span class="insight-detail">South Carolina</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="rate-trends">
            <h4>Rate Trends</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Rate Ranges:</strong> Most states maintain rates between 0.1% and 14.37%
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Wage Bases:</strong> Range from $7,000 to $72,800, with median around $15,000
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>New Employer Rates:</strong> Typically between 1.0% and 4.1%
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Regional Variations:</strong> Western states tend to have higher wage bases
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

